It works by emitting a beam of light or sound and measuring the time it takes for the beam to reflect off of the object and return to the probe. This measurement can then be used to determine the distance or position of the object.

There are two main types of touch probes: contact probes and non-contact probes.

Contact probes make physical contact with the object being measured and use a spring or other type of force to measure the distance. These probes are typically used for high-precision measurements in industrial applications.

Non-contact probes, on the other hand, do not make physical contact with the object and measure the distance using either light or sound. These probes are typically used for measuring larger distances or for measuring objects that are not suitable for contact measurements.

Touch probes are used in a variety of applications, including robotics, automation, and manufacturing. They are also used in research and development, as well as in education and training.
